<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<h1>Paired sample problem</h1>



<h3>Introduction</h3>

Supose that we have a drug that is claimed to reduce blood pressure. We
want to test if it really is effective or not. For this we take n patients
and measure their blood pressures: 
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>.
 The the drug is administered to them and blood pressures are
measured again after the drug has taken its effect. Call the new
measurements as Y<sub>1</sub>,...,Y<sub>n</sub>.
 It is reasonable to assume that 

<blockquote>
(X<sub>1</sub>,Y<sub>1</sub>),...,
(X<sub>n</sub>,Y<sub>n</sub>)
</blockquote>

are indep but not necessarily identically distributed. This is called a
<b>paired sample</b> set up. Define 

<blockquote>
Z<sub>i</sub> = Y<sub>i</sub>-X<sub>i</sub>.
</blockquote>
 
If the drug is really
effective we would expect mmost of the Z's to be positive. If the drug
has no effect then Z's are as likely to be positive as
negative. [Placebo?] In nonparametric statistical inference it is
customary to assume that Z's all have continuous distributions with a
common median, 
               <img src=
               "image/theta.png"
               align=top>
               
                which is unknown. 
^hen the problem is to test 

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: 
               <img src=
               "image/theta.png"
               align=top>
               
                = 0 
Vs H<sub>1</sub>: 
                  <img src=
                  "image/theta.png"
                  align=top>
                  
                    &gt; 0
</blockquote>

We can of course similarly be interested in the other onesided test or a
two sided test. 

<h3>Nonparametric tests</h3>
We have already seen one test for this, viz, the sign test. However, it
uses uses nothing but but the sign sign and hence loses much of the
information present in the data. This is partly remedied in Wilcoxon's
Signed Rank test. 


<table border=0>


<tr>
<td>s<sub>i</sub> = </td>
<td> 1 </td>
<td>if Zi  &gt;  0</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td>   </td>
<td>0 </td>
<td>else</td>
</tr>


</table>


Let R<sub>i</sub> be the ranks of |Z<sub>i</sub>|'s,
 eg, if |Z<sub>7</sub>| is the largest |Z<sub>i</sub>| 
then R<sub>7</sub>=1,
and so on. Then the test statistic is 

<blockquote>
T = 
    <img src=
    "image/sum.gif"
    align=middle>
    
     s<sub>i</sub> R<sub>i</sub>
</blockquote>

It is called Wilcoxon's signed rank statistics. 

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Suppose that the Z<sub>i</sub>'s are
   
   <blockquote>
   1.4 -2.9 2.4 -3.4 5.9 2.5
   </blockquote>
   
   The we compute the following 
   
   <blockquote>
   <pre>
   |Z<sub>i</sub>| 1.4 2.9 2.4 3.4 5.9 2.5
   s<sub>i</sub>    1   0   1   0   1   1
   R<sub>i</sub>    6   3   5   2   1   4
   </pre>
   
   </blockquote>
   
   This produces T = 6+5+1+4 = 16.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
We should reject H<sub>0</sub> if T is large. 


<p><b>Claim:</b>

T is distribution-free under H<sub>0</sub>.

<p>


<p>
   <blockquote>
   <b><i>Justification:</i></b> 
   
   Undr H<sub>0</sub>, Z's are symmetric around 0. So |Z| and s are indep. Since
   R's are functions of |Z|'s, hence the s's are indep of the R's. Also s's are
   iid Bern(1/2) under H<sub>0</sub>. 
   
   <p>Let's compute the conditional null distribution of 
   T|R<sub>i</sub>'s = 
                       <img src=
                       "image/sum.gif"
                       align=middle>
                       
                       s<sub>i</sub>R<sub>i</sub>
   R<sub>i</sub>. 
   In this conditional distribution, Ri's are just some <i>fixed</i>
   permutation of {1,...,n}. Multiplying them with si's and adding, amounts
   to performing iid unbaised coin tosses for each i, and then add the Ri's
   corresponding to the heads. This distribution obviously does not depend
   upon the permutation. So T is indep of the R<sub>i</sub>'s and T is
   distribution-free under H<sub>0</sub>. 
   
   <b>///</b>
   </blockquote>
   

<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
<td>
<b>Exercise:</b> 

Why is |Z| indep of s if Z has distribution symmetric around 0?

</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>


<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
<td>
<b>Exercise:</b> 

Compute the distribution of T explicitly for n = 4.

</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Exercise:</b> 
   
   Show that E(T) = n(n+1)/4 and V(T) = n(n+1)(2n+1)/24.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Exercise:</b> 
   
   Write a computer program to verify the upper-tail probabilities
   mentioned in table a.4 of the Myles and Hollander for n=10.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
<h3>Why is the symmetry assumption reasonable?</h3>
Note that Wilcoxon's signed rank test uses more information than the sign
test. But it also requires an extra symmetry assumption. This assumption
is often a reasonable one as we see below.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Let X be the blood pressure of some patient before the treatment, and let
   Y be that after the treatment. Asue that X,Y are independent and that
   their distrn differs only in location. 
   
   <p><center>
   <img src="image/locshift.gif">
   </center><p>
   
   In other word, if X ~ F and Y ~ G, then 
   
   <blockquote>
   F(x) = G(x-
              <img src=
              "image/theta.png"
              align=top>
              
              ) 
   for some 
            <img src=
            "image/theta.png"
            align=top>
            
             
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Exercise:</b> 
   
   Show that in this case X-Y has distribution symmetric around 
   
   <img src=
   "image/theta.png"
   align=top>
   
   .
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


